          "id": "music-history-101-l07-c1",
          "title": "Emotion Over Form",
          "content": "The Romantic period, which spanned from 1820 to 1900, was a fascinating time in music history when composers began to prioritize their personal feelings and emotions over strict musical rules and structures. This shift allowed musicians to express themselves in new and exciting ways. During this era, orchestras grew significantly in size, which meant that they could produce a much wider range of sounds and emotional experiences. Composers also started to experiment with chromaticism, which involves using notes that fall outside of the traditional scales. This added a rich variety of colors to their music. Many composers drew inspiration from different sources, such as literature, the beauty of nature, and their own personal experiences and emotions. This was a dramatic change from the Classical period, where the focus was more on refined craftsmanship and formal structures. In the Romantic era, artists were celebrated as geniuses who conveyed deep feelings through their music, making this a thrilling time for creativity and expression in the world of music.\nContext recap: The Romantic period, which spanned from 1820 to 1900, was a fascinating time in music history when composers began to prioritize their personal feelings and emotions over strict musical rules and structures. This shift allowed musicians to express themselves in new and exciting ways. During this era, orchestras grew significantly in size, which meant that they could produce a much wider range of sounds and emotional experiences. Composers also started to experiment with chromaticism, which involves using notes that fall outside of the traditional scales."
