          "id": "music-history-101-l07-c2",
          "title": "Piano Virtuosity and Art Song",
          "content": "During the Romantic period, two remarkable composers, Frédéric Chopin and Franz Liszt, changed the way we think about the piano. They turned it into a powerful tool for expressing deep emotions and showcasing extraordinary talent. Chopin is well-known for his beautiful compositions, such as nocturnes, preludes, and ballades. These pieces are celebrated for their intimate and emotional qualities, allowing listeners to feel a wide range of feelings. On the other hand, Liszt took piano music to new heights with his transcendental études, which are incredibly challenging and demonstrate the technical possibilities of the instrument.\nIn addition to piano music, the art song, or Lied, became very popular during this time. This genre involves setting poems to music for a solo singer, accompanied by a piano. One of the most famous composers of art songs was Franz Schubert, who wrote an astonishing collection of over 600 songs. Among his most notable works is the song cycle 'Winterreise,' which tells the poignant story of a heartbroken lover as he wanders through a cold, wintry landscape, filled with feelings of sadness and longing. This combination of music and poetry made the art song a cherished form of expression in the Romantic era.\nContext recap: During the Romantic period, two remarkable composers, Frédéric Chopin and Franz Liszt, changed the way we think about the piano. They turned it into a powerful tool for expressing deep emotions and showcasing extraordinary talent. Chopin is well-known for his beautiful compositions, such as nocturnes, preludes, and ballades. These pieces are celebrated for their intimate and emotional qualities, allowing listeners to feel a wide range of feelings.\nWhy this matters: Piano Virtuosity and Art Song helps learners in Music connect ideas from Music History: Medieval to Modern to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Connect ideas to real decisions and evidence."
