          "id": "music-history-101-l13-c2",
          "title": "Electronic Music and Hip-Hop",
          "content": "In the 1960s, a groundbreaking invention called the synthesizer was introduced, with the Moog being one of the first models. This amazing instrument allowed musicians to create unique sounds that traditional acoustic instruments, like pianos and guitars, could not replicate. One of the most influential bands of this time was Kraftwerk, a German group that led the way in electronic pop music during the 1970s. They showcased how these new electronic sounds could be used creatively in music. At the same time, a new genre called hip-hop was born in the South Bronx in 1973. Hip-hop artists used turntables, drum machines, and sampling techniques to create fresh music by reimagining existing recordings. This innovative approach turned DJs and producers into the new musicians of the era, as they crafted beats and rhythms that resonated with audiences. Additionally, electronic dance music, or EDM, began to rise in popularity, moving from small underground clubs to large mainstream music festivals. These events attracted huge crowds, as people danced to the energetic beats and exciting rhythms that defined this vibrant genre of music.\nContext recap: In the 1960s, a groundbreaking invention called the synthesizer was introduced, with the Moog being one of the first models. This amazing instrument allowed musicians to create unique sounds that traditional acoustic instruments, like pianos and guitars, could not replicate. One of the most influential bands of this time was Kraftwerk, a German group that led the way in electronic pop music during the 1970s. They showcased how these new electronic sounds could be used creatively in music.\nWhy this matters: Electronic Music and Hip-Hop helps learners in Music connect ideas from Music History: Medieval to Modern to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Connect ideas to real decisions and evidence."
