          "id": "music-history-101-l13-c3",
          "title": "The Digital Age",
          "content": "The MP3 format, introduced in the 1990s, and the launch of Napster in 1999 brought about a major transformation in the music industry. These innovations made it much easier for people to share music digitally, allowing songs to be shared across the internet with just a few clicks. In 2003, Apple released iTunes, which played a crucial role in making digital music sales popular and legitimate. This platform allowed music lovers to buy and download their favorite songs conveniently, changing how we access music. Then, in 2008, streaming services like Spotify emerged, giving listeners the ability to enjoy almost all recorded music for a monthly subscription fee. This meant that anyone could explore a vast library of music from around the world without needing to buy individual songs. Nowadays, with just a laptop or a smartphone, anyone can create their own music and share it with audiences globally. This new digital landscape has made it easier for artists to connect with their fans, but it has also sparked important discussions about how musicians are compensated for their work and how music is selected and promoted in this digital age. As we navigate this exciting era, it's essential to think about the balance between accessibility and fair treatment for artists.\nContext recap: The MP3 format, introduced in the 1990s, and the launch of Napster in 1999 brought about a major transformation in the music industry. These innovations made it much easier for people to share music digitally, allowing songs to be shared across the internet with just a few clicks. In 2003, Apple released iTunes, which played a crucial role in making digital music sales popular and legitimate. This platform allowed music lovers to buy and download their favorite songs conveniently, changing how we access music.\nWhy this matters: The Digital Age helps learners in Music connect ideas from Music History: Medieval to Modern to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Connect ideas to real decisions and evidence."
