          "id": "music-history-101-l14-c1",
          "title": "Common Misconceptions",
          "content": "Let's explore some common misunderstandings about classical music that can help us appreciate it even more! First, many people think that when we say 'classical music,' we are talking about all old orchestral music. However, 'classical' actually refers to a specific time period in music history that lasted from 1750 to 1820. This period is just one part of a larger category called 'Western art music,' which includes many different styles and eras of orchestral music from various times in history.\nAnother myth is about the famous composer Johann Sebastian Bach. Some might believe that he was very well-known during his lifetime, but that's not quite true. While Bach was recognized as a talented organist, his compositions were not widely appreciated until many years later. It wasn't until the composer Felix Mendelssohn revived Bach's music in 1829 that people began to recognize his genius.\nLastly, there's a common belief that older music is not relevant to the music we hear today. This is definitely a misconception! In fact, many popular songs today use a chord progression known as I-V-vi-IV, which is very similar to the harmonic patterns that Bach used in his own compositions. By understanding these facts, we can see the connections between the music of the past and the music we enjoy today, making our musical journey even more exciting and meaningful!\nContext recap: Let's explore some common misunderstandings about classical music that can help us appreciate it even more! First, many people think that when we say 'classical music,' we are talking about all old orchestral music. However, 'classical' actually refers to a specific time period in music history that lasted from 1750 to 1820. This period is just one part of a larger category called 'Western art music,' which includes many different styles and eras of orchestral music from various times in history.\nWhy this matters: Common Misconceptions helps learners in Music connect ideas from Music History: Medieval to Modern to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Connect ideas to real decisions and evidence.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
